            <fr:title text="Banach Space">Banach Space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A Banach space is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0023.xml" addr="FA-0023" title="Complete">complete</fr:link> <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0043">normed vector space</fr:link>. That is, a Banach space is a vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> with a <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0044">norm</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||\cdot ||]]></fr:tex> such that every <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0033.xml" addr="FA-0033" title="Cauchy sequence">Cauchy sequence</fr:link> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> (with respect to the metric <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(u, v) = ||u - v||]]></fr:tex>) converges to a vector in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Banach spaces are fundamental in functional analysis and named after Stefan Banach. They provide the right setting for many important results in analysis, including the Hahn-Banach theorem, the open mapping theorem, and the closed graph theorem.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Examples include the spaces <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \geq  1]]></fr:tex>, the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C([a,b])]]></fr:tex> of continuous functions on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[a,b]]]></fr:tex> with the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0014.xml" addr="FA-0014" title="Sup norm">sup norm</fr:link>, and all finite-dimensional normed vector spaces.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>949</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0030</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0030.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Hilbert Space">Hilbert Space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A Hilbert space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0023.xml" addr="FA-0023" title="Complete">complete</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0038.xml" addr="FA-0038" title="Inner product space">inner product space</fr:link>. That is, a Hilbert space is a vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> with an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0039.xml" addr="FA-0039" title="Inner product">inner product</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[<\cdot ,\cdot >]]></fr:tex> such that the norm defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||x|| = \sqrt {<x,x>}]]></fr:tex> makes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> into a complete metric space.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Hilbert spaces extend the methods of linear algebra to infinite-dimensional settings, making them crucial for quantum mechanics, Fourier analysis, and partial differential equations.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Examples include the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^2]]></fr:tex> of square-integrable functions and the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[l^2]]></fr:tex> of square-summable sequences.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>951</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0038</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0038.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Inner product space">Inner product space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>An inner product space is a vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> over the field of real or complex numbers, equipped with an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0039.xml" addr="FA-0039" title="Inner product">inner product</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[<\cdot ,\cdot >: V \times  V \rightarrow  \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The inner product satisfies the following axioms for all vectors <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u, v, w \in  V]]></fr:tex> and all scalars <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a \in  \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li><fr:strong>Linearity in the first argument:</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[<au + v, w> = a<u, w> + <v, w>]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:strong>Conjugate symmetry:</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[<u, v> = \overline {<v, u>}]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:strong>Positive definiteness:</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[<v, v> \geq  0]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[<v, v> = 0]]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v = 0]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>From the inner product, we can define:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>A norm: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||v|| = \sqrt {<v,v>}]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>A metric: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(u,v) = ||u-v||]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>The concept of orthogonality: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> are orthogonal if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[<u,v> = 0]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>Common examples of inner product spaces include <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex> with the dot product, the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C([a,b])]]></fr:tex> with the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^2]]></fr:tex>-inner product <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  f,g \rangle  = \int _a^b f(x)\overline {g(x)}dx]]></fr:tex>, and the space of square-integrable functions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^2]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>A <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0030.xml" addr="FA-0030" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> is a complete inner product space.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>953</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0016</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0016.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Metric Space">Metric Space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A metric space is a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> together with a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0009.xml" addr="FA-0009" title="Distance Measure">distance measure</fr:link> (or metric) <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d]]></fr:tex> that defines a concept of distance between any two members of the set.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The metric satisfies the following properties:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>Non-negativity: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,y) \geq  0]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Identity of indiscernibles: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,y) = 0]]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = y]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Symmetry: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,y) = d(y,x)]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Triangle inequality: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,z) \leq  d(x,y) + d(y,z)]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
